SIMPLE: fast
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fast
<hw>Fast</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Fasted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fasting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>f⟦ae⟧stan</ets>;
<ets>akin to D</ets>. <ets>vasten</ets>, OHG. <ets>fast⟦emac⟧n</ets>, G.
<ets>fasten</ets>, Icel. & Sw. <ets>fasta</ets>, Dan. <ets>faste</ets>,
Goth. <ets>fastan</ets> to keep, observe, fast, and prob. to E.
<ets>fast</ets> firm.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To abstain from food; to
omit to take nourishment in whole or in part; to go hungry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Fasting</qex> he went to sleep, and <qex>fasting</qex>
waked.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To practice abstinence as a religious exercise or
duty; to abstain from food voluntarily for a time, for the mortification
of the body or appetites, or as a token of grief, or humiliation and
penitence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou didst <qex>fast</qex> and weep for the child.</q> <rj><qau>2
Sam. xii. 21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fasting day</b></col>, <cd>a fast day; a day of
fasting.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fast</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fast
<hw>Fast</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>faste</ets>,
<ets>fast</ets>; cf. AS. <ets>f⟦ae⟧sten</ets>, OHG. <ets>fasta</ets>, G.
<ets>faste</ets>. See <er>Fast</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Abstinence from food; omission to take nourishment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Surfeit is the father of much <qex>fast</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Voluntary abstinence from food, for a space of time,
as a spiritual discipline, or as a token of religious
humiliation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A time of fasting, whether a day, week, or longer
time; a period of abstinence from food or certain kinds of food; <as>as,
an annual <ex>fast</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fast day</b></col>, <cd>a day appointed for fasting,
humiliation, and religious offices as a means of invoking the favor of
God.</cd> -- <col><b>To break one's fast</b></col>, <cd>to put an end to
a period of abstinence by taking food; especially, to take one's morning
meal; to breakfast.</cd> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fast</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fast
<hw>Fast</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Faster</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Fastest</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE., firm, strong,
not loose, AS. <ets>f⟦ae⟧st</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>fast</ets>, D.
<ets>vast</ets>, OHG. <ets>fasti</ets>, <ets>festi</ets>, G.
<ets>fest</ets>, Icel. <ets>fastr</ets>, Sw. & Dan. <ets>fast</ets>, and
perh. to E. <ets>fetter</ets>. The sense <ets>swift</ets> comes from the
idea of keeping close to what is pursued; a Scandinavian use. Cf.
<er>Fast</er>, <pos>adv.</pos>, <er>Fast</er>, <pos>v.</pos>,
<er>Avast</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Firmly fixed; closely adhering;
made firm; not loose, unstable, or easily moved; immovable; <as>as, to
make <ex>fast</ex> the door</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is an order that keeps things <qex>fast</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Firm against attack; fortified by nature or art;
impregnable; strong.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Outlaws . . . lurking in woods and <qex>fast</qex> places.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Firm in adherence; steadfast; not easily separated
or alienated; faithful; <as>as, a <ex>fast</ex> friend</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Permanent; not liable to fade by exposure to air or
by washing; durable; lasting; <as>as, <ex>fast</ex>
colors</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Tenacious; retentive.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Roses, damask and red, are <qex>fast</qex> flowers of their
smells.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Not easily disturbed or broken; deep;
sound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All this while in a most <qex>fast</qex> sleep.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Moving rapidly; quick in mition; rapid; swift;
<as>as, a <ex>fast</ex> horse</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Given to pleasure seeking; disregardful of
restraint; reckless; wild; dissipated; dissolute; <as>as, a
<ex>fast</ex> man; a <ex>fast</ex> liver.</as></def>
<rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>In such a condition, as to resilience, etc., as to
make possible unusual rapidity of play or action; <as>as, a
<ex>fast</ex> racket, or tennis court; a <ex>fast</ex> track; a
<ex>fast</ex> billiard table, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fast and loose</b></col>, <cd>now cohering, now
disjoined; inconstant, esp. in the phrases <xex>to play at fast and
loose</xex>, <xex>to play fast and loose</xex>, to act with giddy or
reckless inconstancy or in a tricky manner; to say one thing and do
another.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Play fast and loose</xex> with faith.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>Fast and loose pulleys</b></col>
<fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>two pulleys placed side by side on a revolving
shaft, which is driven from another shaft by a band, and arranged to
disengage and re⟦eum⟧ngage the machinery driven thereby. When the
machinery is to be stopped, the band is transferred from the pulley
fixed to the shaft to the pulley which revolves freely upon it, and
<xex>vice versa</xex>.</cd> -- <col><b>Hard and fast</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>so completely aground as to be immovable.</cd>
-- <col><b>To make fast</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to make
secure; to fasten firmly, as a vessel, a rope, or a door.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 545 --></p>

<p><ent>Fast</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Fast
<hw>Fast</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>faste</ets>
firmly, strongly, quickly, AS. <ets>f⟦ae⟧ste</ets>. See <er>Fast</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>In a fast, fixed, or firmly
established manner; fixedly; firmly; immovably.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We will bind thee <qex>fast</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Judg. xv.
13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In a fast or rapid manner; quickly; swiftly;
extravagantly; wildly; <as>as, to run <ex>fast</ex>; to live
<ex>fast</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Fast by</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Fast
beside</b></col></mcol>, <cd>close or near to; near at
hand.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He, after Eve seduced, unminded slunk⟦br⟧
Into the wood <qex>fast by</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Fast by</qex> the throne obsequious Fame resides.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fast</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Fast
<hw>Fast</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>That which fastens or holds;
especially, <fld>(Naut.)</fld> a mooring rope, hawser, or chain; --
called, according to its position, a <xex>bow</xex>, <xex>head</xex>,
<xex>quarter</xex>, <xex>breast</xex>, or <xex>stern fast</xex>; also, a
post on a pier around which hawsers are passed in mooring.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>fastball</ent>⟦br⟧
